From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: tonytranrp <100391458+tonytranrp@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Mon, 15 Jun 2026 00:48:07 -1000
Subject: [PATCH] clang-mg: add hard test for compact size tie-break

Equal-alignment fields are ordered by descending size (then source order). A char array and a char share alignment 1 but the array, being larger, precedes the scalar. Full order by alignment: int, short, char[4], char. Ground truth from the layout dump.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

diff --git a/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-size-tiebreak.cpp b/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-size-tiebreak.cpp
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..c49d56cab
--- /dev/null
+++ b/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-size-tiebreak.cpp
@@ -0,0 +1,22 @@
+// HARD: the compact comparator sorts by DESCENDING ALIGNMENT, then DESCENDING
+// SIZE as a tie-break (then source order). Here char[4] (big) and char (small)
+// share alignment 1 but differ in size, so big must precede small. The full
+// order by alignment is {int(4), short(2), char[4](1,sz4), char(1,sz1)}.
+//
+// RUN: %clang_cc1 -std=c++20 -fcxxmg -fsyntax-only -fdump-record-layouts %s | FileCheck %s
+
+compact struct S {
+  char small;
+  char big[4];
+  short s;
+  int x;
+};
+S v;
+
+static_assert(sizeof(S) == 12, "int(4)+short(2)+char[4]+char, padded to 12");
+
+// CHECK:      struct S
+// CHECK-NEXT: int x
+// CHECK-NEXT: short s
+// CHECK-NEXT: char[4] big
+// CHECK-NEXT: char small
-- 
